WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
Hi everyone, I'm super excited to be here.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:15.120
So this is my last slide and I'm going to go back to the beginning.

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:20.360
So that was a quick preview of what I'm going to talk about.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:23.040
So I'm going to talk today about being an R blogger.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:27.959
So here on my first slide are many ways in which you can get in touch with me.

00:00:27.959 --> 00:00:28.959
Feel free to take a photo.

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:32.279
Thank you, that's very nice.

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:35.040
So I have a website, maybe some of you have seen it before.

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:42.080
I write a lot of blogs about R packages, about statistics stuff, sometimes just about random

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:47.520
opinions that no one cares about, but you know, it's fun, it's a great way to procrastinate.

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:51.320
I would like to talk first about, okay, if you're interested in starting a blog, what

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:52.919
are the main reasons you might want to do that?

00:00:52.919 --> 00:00:54.959
So the first one is to learn something.

00:00:54.959 --> 00:00:59.360
You never realize how little you know until you have to explain it to someone else.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:02.520
Writing a blog is a great way of realizing that.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:08.279
Another reason is, this is actually one of my main motivations, which was, like, I really

00:01:08.279 --> 00:01:13.000
enjoy teaching and I wanted a series of examples of my teaching.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.239
So if you have a blog where you explain a lot of things, it shows that you know how

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:19.959
to explain a lot of things, so that's pretty great.

00:01:19.959 --> 00:01:23.599
I also feel like it's a really great way to practice your communication skills, for which

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:25.559
there's often not that many opportunities.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:30.080
You know, if you're in academia, writing scientific papers is usually a good way to practice poor

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.919
communication skills.

00:01:32.919 --> 00:01:35.959
This is my favorite, which is procrastination.

00:01:35.959 --> 00:01:39.279
So I often have those days where I just can't actually do any of the things I'm supposed

00:01:39.279 --> 00:01:43.720
to be doing, and really I just want to go home, but probably I shouldn't do that, so

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:47.160
maybe I'll do something else that makes it feel like I'm being productive, such as write

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:48.160
a blog post.

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.680
Okay, so now that I've convinced you all that you want to write blog posts, how do you choose

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:54.599
what to write about?

00:01:54.599 --> 00:01:59.360
So what I normally do is I write about something that I just learned, especially if I had a

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:01.160
hard time learning about it.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:04.839
So if you are trying to learn something and there's no resources out there, that's a really,

00:02:04.839 --> 00:02:08.679
really good indication that there need to be some good resources out there.

00:02:08.679 --> 00:02:12.919
So you know, why not help everyone else not go through what you just went through?

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:15.479
The other is I write about things that I want to learn.

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:17.960
So that's what I did with the Purr package, for example.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:21.000
I was like, I know I should know more about Purr.

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:24.279
So I was like, I'm going to write a blog post about it, and then I learned so much, and

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:25.279
it was great.

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:27.800
Okay, so how do you write a blog?

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:29.919
So the blogdown package is amazing.

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:34.320
It's essentially a way of collecting together a bunch of R Markdown documents into a web

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:35.320
page.

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:42.399
I also host my, so I have a GitHub repository in which my public folder from the blogdown

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:48.360
rendering exists, and if you use Netlify, you can essentially have it point to your

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.240
Git repo, and then every time you push to your Git repo, it automatically updates your

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:54.240
website.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:58.039
So it's very little overhead compared with something like GitHub Pages.

00:02:58.039 --> 00:03:01.679
I also wrote a post about this like three years ago.

00:03:01.679 --> 00:03:04.520
I'll show a link to my slides at the end, so this is probably hard to see.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:06.520
It's kind of at the bottom.

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:09.160
Okay, so you should also use relevant and interesting data.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:15.039
So this is a photo of an iris plant as a great example.

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:20.119
So I also like to do something where instead of downloading, instead of having people download

00:03:20.119 --> 00:03:24.399
data and then having to load it in manually, I try to have it so that you can load it in

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:27.320
line using a URL.

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:32.240
So it just makes it so that it's a lot easier for your readers to follow along.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:35.360
You also want to keep everything really simple, like explain it to your grandma, don't explain

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:36.360
it to an expert.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:39.800
Like the people that are reading this are people that probably like need some help,

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:43.880
and like I used to kind of preface by saying sorry if I'm giving too much detail, and people

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:47.399
would be like that was not too much detail, that was like spot on, and that was really

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:48.399
nice.

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:51.720
Like I literally explained something using stick figures once, and it was great.

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:54.919
Okay, so now you've written all this stuff, how do you get the word out there?

00:03:54.919 --> 00:03:57.720
So honestly the best way to do that is to tweet about it.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:01.800
I am not a big Twitter person.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.080
I think people think that I am because like when I do tweet, there's like a lot of kind

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:09.800
of spreading, but it's like I tweet once every three months, and it's usually like hey, here's

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:13.839
a blog post, and that's been so far the best way for kind of showing people that I've written

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:14.839
a new blog post.

00:04:14.839 --> 00:04:20.320
Something else that I do is I try to use easily Googleable titles.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:26.040
For example, Max will like this one, I have a carrot tutorial, which is if you just literally

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:30.399
type in carrot tutorial, it's the second thing that pops up in Google, and the title is basic

00:04:30.399 --> 00:04:35.040
tutorial of carrot, like that's going to come up, which is kind of nice.

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:41.640
Another thing to do is to like present, you know, like go to our ladies, give a tutorial

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:46.959
or your company or your university, and there's a lot of ways to kind of spread the things

00:04:46.959 --> 00:04:51.079
that you've learned and that you want to share and explain, and it's a really, really great

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:52.839
way to practice.

00:04:52.839 --> 00:04:55.359
So here's a link to my slides at the top.

00:04:55.359 --> 00:04:57.040
Go forth and blog.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:04:58.040
Thank you.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:04:58.040


